{"key":"post-9888812","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9888812</id>\n<content>Correct. Fully colonized mycelium will hardly ever contaminate.&amp;nbsp; Fresh air is the number 1 pinning trigger, and also the number 1 contamination prevention in fruiting chambers.&amp;nbsp; Molds thrive in still, stale air, and mushrooms thrive in moving, fresh air.&amp;nbsp; You can fruit your substrate trays of colonized coir in any fruiting chamber that will give you a constant supply of fresh air, while also providing humidity control.&amp;nbsp; A well ventilated mini-greenhouse, or a large &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;shotgun terrarium&lt;/a&gt; will work well for that.&amp;nbsp; Filtering is unnecessary in the fruiting stage, and actually counter-productive, since it impedes the flow of fresh air.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9888850</next>\n<prev>9888793</prev>\n<first>9888270</first>\n<last>9889953</last>\n<when>1235918851</when>\n<utime>03/01/09 04:47 PM</utime>\n</post>"}